Rating: 0
I haven't made this cake yet. But after reading the reviews, I want to offer some tips that may help you with baking chiffon cakes: 1. Don't grease the pan. 2. Whip the egg yolks until foamy. Add in the sugar, a little at a time. Beat well after each addition. Beat the yolks until the mixture is thickened to the point that it can form a ribbon when you pull up the beater. 3. Beat oil into the yolk mixture, a little at a time. 4. After the oil and yolks have completely incorporated, add in all the water. Mix well. 5. When you measure the flour, spoon the flour into the cup and then level with a knife. 6. Sift the flour for at least 3 times. 7. Use a wire whisk to fold in the egg whites. 8. Make sure that the oven is well-preheated. Happy baking!

Rating: 4
I also had trouble finding unsalted pistachios, and ended up washing them. I used three 9-inch pans and increased the whipped cream by 1/2 cup, thinking I would not have enough to cover. I did end up having left over frosting. My main recommendation: make this cake in winter, not on a humid June day. Reduce the lemon zest and increase the cardamom (ground). I might look into using another sponge recipe too, because when I had all the non egg-white ingredients together, it wasn't batter, it was tough dough. Finally, use your hands to cover the rose petals with eggwhite foam rather than a pastry brush, it's just easier (and keep the rose petals off the cake if you are storing it for more than a few hours). Family gave this rave reviews.

