Rating: 4
Continuation: For the frosting, I used 2 pinches of saffron threads and did not strain them out as I love the exotic look they lend the white whipped cream. Also, I only used a total of 1 ¾ cup of heavy cream because the amount listed would have yielded too much for my liking. I zapped the beater, bowl, saffron cream, heavy whipping cream, powdered sugar, and the rose water in the freezer for 10 minutes before starting. Using a bowl full of ice water under the KitchenAid bowl allowed all the ingredients to remain very cold while whipping. It took only 4-5 minutes on speed 6 for it to become frosting. For the garnish, I could only find salted pistachios so I rinsed them well in a colander for 4 minutes under the cold water spray head and their brown skin peeled right off. The cake looked absolutely adorable with the dried cranberries arranged into a large heart shape on the top with the pistachios strewn around and on the sides. I also added about two pinches of lemon rind to the center of the heart for added adornment. The cake tasted heavenly and was oh-so fluffy. My family was VERY skeptical about this cake as they are junkies for dense rich cakes but I was able to win them over with this one! Next time, I will use pomegranate and almonds to garnish the cake instead. This project took me nearly 4.5 hours but now that Ive completed this first trial run, I believe it should only take me 2 hours the next time I make Persian Love Cake.

