I dont remember how I stumbled upon this recipe for Persian Love Cake, but I do know that once I read it over, I became obsessive about making it! I did extensive planning and research for about a week before getting down to business. I read every blog I could find and studied these reviews like a student before an exam. I had no trouble finding rosewater at our local Pakistani/Indian grocery but not for the life of me could I find unsprayed roses anywhere. I searched and called dozens of places but to no avail. Thus, being more than a little disappointed about not having the keystone ingredient, I used dried cranberries that I had on hand in its place. I created a master list of alterations and tips to the recipe: I used two 8 x 1.5 pans with only a circle of parchment paper on the bottom, absolutely no grease anywhere. For the batter, I increased the cardamom to 8 pods, grinding them finely with a mortar and pestle. In addition to increasing the lemon rind to 1.5 teaspoons, I added a few strands of saffron to the batter as well. I increased the egg whites to 4 and made sure that they were room temperature before whipping. I squeezed in a little more than an 1/8 teaspoon of lemon juice to help the egg whites form stiff peaks. The cake took 35 minutes to bake. Upon exiting the oven, I immediately took them out of the pans and rested them on a wire rack to cool. Leaving the cakes in their pans would lock in steam which deflates them.

