Rating: 4
Excellent! CRUSH the cardamom seeds, do NOT GREASE the pan, do use the parchment in the bottom of the pan, and do use 5 EGG WHITES in the cake. These previous suggestions from other reviewers made the cake fail-safe. Don't worry about runny icing--just keep whipping it, and it will reward you. The chiffon cake and whipped icing are like eating a gently spiced cloud. I made it (the first time I have tried baking a cake in YEARS) as a wedding cake: 3 full batches to make a two-tier cake. And I recommend a cake leveler to split the layers to add the moist frosting as much as possible in between the cake layers. I used odd-sized pans to get the tiers to my liking, and followed the instructions for baking that came with the pans--a higher temperature, mostly--and they came out lovely. I skipped the rose petals due to source issues and used prefab sugar orchids from the craft store. Not truly edible on their wire foundations, but easy and beautiful. The frosting is so forgiving that even on disassembling the tiers, a quick flick of a spatula erased all hint of anything resting on the cake surface. It was such a pretty icing I didn't even think of piping it with my cake decoator set. And I usually dread the icing stage because it is when a cake can so easily become Franken-Cake. Not with this forgiving frosting! The pistachios are just the right color touch at the finish, and are fun to throw at the sides of the cake--they stick if you toss 'em hard enough! DO make this cake! It is lovely, and only gets more moist as it sits in the refrigerator. The icing has not, as I worried it would, gone liquid even days and days later. So easy, so delicious. The foodie newlyweds were awed, and so were the guests--and so was I because it had all been too easy.

