This was by far one of the most interesting and truly splendid cakes I have ever made! And b/c of no butter and/or oil, one of the lightest. I made this for a friend's birthday and it was a resounding success! It was met with "ooohs" and "aaahs" and people asking "how did you make that? that's amazing!" I was very pleased. Some things I did differently: I didn't bother with the rosewater, I went straight for rose essence. I'm Indian and these flavours are common in our sweets so I felt comfortable working with them. What the recipe calls for is way too little. You'd barely get any flavor at all if you followed the original recipe. Anyway, I put approx 1/2 tsp of rose essence into the whipping cream (just adjust to taste) and for the saffron, I definitely added at least 3 pinches. Trust me, it was not overpowering, instead, it yielded a lovely flavor. Also, for the cardamom, I had about twice the amount of pods they recommended. I crushed them with a mortar & pestle and coarsely ground them. Biting into a whole cardamom is kind of gross. Finally, I doubled the recipe and used 2 9x13 pans. I then stacked on top of one another on a beautiful white serving platter. I sprinkled the rose petals and pistachios on top and then I used the remaining 4 whole rosebuds as decoration on the 4 corners of my cake. People were freaking out, I kid you not! This cake was beyond good! Such a nice alternative to chocolate, etc.

