Rating: 3
As a note about using raw eggs to "candy" rose petals. I have used raw eggs extensively to "frost" fruits such as grapes, cherries, pears and kumquats. I have also used much the same recipe to candy violets and pansies. Since sugar (a preservative and anti-bacterial agent) is used, I am not fearful of using raw eggs. The only issue in using such a recipe is to make sure that the fruit and/or flowers are unblemished and completly dry. I have kept candied pansies and violets in an airtight, dark container for up to a year. Never have I had any problems as long as enough sugar was used to absorb the egg white.

Rating: 0
sorry, I haven't made the recipe, but how great actually is the risk of salmonella? I've eaten raw cookie dough by the pound, made Caesar Salad with raw egg, and used plenty of raw eggs in various recipes. I DO always wash the outside of the shell, before I crack the egg. I have NEVER heard of anyone I know getting sick from ice cream, cookie dough, salad dressing....if salmonella is not a problem in your area, and you are using fresh, hygenic, organic eggs, is this a realistic fear?

Rating: 0
I hate to clog up reviews with comments that do not refer to the recipe, and this is the first time I've done it, but the comment about egg safety is flat out wrong! Any time you are using raw eggs you are at risk of salmonella. The only way to be completely sure is to use cooked or pasturized eggs. And salmonella is actually on the OUTside of the egg, although there are a few strains (out of hundreds) that can easily penetrate the shell. If you're not sure who to believe, look it up somewhere else like the cdc.gov

Rating: 0
To: A Cook on 07/02/05 Remember to use pasturized eggs when making the candied rose petals. Salmonella, anyone? It isn't the egg white that you have to worry about it is only the yolks that carry Salmonella. So, as long as you don't break any of the yolk when separating whites from yolks, you're ok.

