Rating: 3
This is a delightful cake which I have made several times to rave reviews. As was previously noted, the cake is not overly sweet, which I find to be a good thing. While this recipe has no real connection to traditional Persian cuisine, it is an imaginative non-traditional vehicle for incorporating the flavours of cardamom, rose water and saffron, found in so many traditional Persian desserts. The frosting is pleasant (just go lightly on the rose water), and the chiffon cake alone is excellent and versatile enough to use as the basis for other cake and dessert creations. In the preparation, I strongly feel the cardamom seeds should be coarsely ground. They are a disruptive texture in the cake and can be rather hard when bitten into. Visually, they are esthetically displeasing. (you can figure out what they might remind one of) A course grind will provide a sufficient "burst of flavour". The presentation of the cake can be enhanced by baking it in one 8 x 3 inch cake pan (for app. 40 minutes) and slicing into three layers. You can also use more filling between the layers (1 1/2 to 2 cups). With the frosting ingredient quantities listed in the recipe, I was able to fill and cover a three layer cake, pipe some simple decorations and still have almost 2 cups of frosting left over. In spite of what may be perceived as criticism, I do think this is a wonderful cake and it has found a solid place in my cake repertoire. Had the cardamom seeds been ground and the cake presented with three layers, it would have rated a firm 4 forks.

